{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d527e6e4-baa6-423a-a032-9a4853afd5d1","content":"This repo doesn't contain documentation on crash dump recovery, so here's the general guidance from .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS defaults to `/cores`):\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** macOS will write a Mach-O core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **Check for Apple's crash reports** in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files contain stack traces and register state.\n\n5. **Analyze the core dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Then use `bt` (backtrace), `thread list`, `register read`, etc.\n\n6. **For managed stack traces**, load the SOS debugging extension in `lldb` if you have the .NET runtime installed:\n   ```bash\n   (lldb) plugin load libsosplugin.dylib\n   ```\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT binaries include native symbols, so `lldb` can usually show meaningful backtraces even without SOS. If you need richer .NET diagnostics, consider setting `COMPlus_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` and `COMPlus_DbgMiniDumpType=4` as environment variables before running the app.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"165e6f49-64f6-4b5b-b36f-0991ac6f62c4","outputTokens":415,"requestId":"608F:2A830E:2F5BBF:3D5CE1:69FFE487"},"id":"bca82c43-7b87-4ed4-a5d5-15b9e1f00ae3","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:51:14.012Z","parentId":"309f096d-8435-445f-a532-17c9acbb4535"}
